Sure! Below you will find a simple example showcasing how HTML (HyperText Markup Language), CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) , and JavaScript work together to create interactive web content.

HTML: Structure
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Interactive Button</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>

<div id="app">
    <button id="myButton">Click me!</button>
</div>

<script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS: Styling (styles.css)
```css
#app {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  height: 100vh; /* Fill the entire viewport */
}

button {
  padding: 10px 20px;
  font-size: 16px;
  cursor: pointer;
}
```

JavaScript: Behavior (script.js)
```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {

    var myButton = document.getElementById("myButton");

    myButton.onclick = function() {
        alert("You clicked the button!");
    };

});
```

In this example:

- The HTML code creates a simple web page with one interactive element, which is an `button` inside of a div.
- CSS provides styling for both the entire app container (`#app`) and specifically styles to make our "Click me!" text visually appealing. It centers everything on screen using Flexbox properties applied in #app's ID selector along with basic button styling rules under its child (the button) style definition block.
- JavaScript waits until all HTML content is fully loaded by listening for the 'DOMContentLoaded' event, then attaches an `onclick` handler to our interactive element - once clicked. In this case of clicking on it will display a simple alert message.

You can save these snippets into their respective files (`index.html`, `styles.css`, and `script.js`) in your local development environment or repository (such as GitHub) if you'd like them there for reference, to edit later based upon what you need. You would also want more advanced features such as form validations, interactive charts with D3.js, etc., depending on the purpose of this page/application you're building.

Remember that it is a good practice not just in terms of best practices but from an accessibility point-of-view (e.g., ensuring text alternatives for non-text content), to adhere certain coding standards like WCAG/WAI-ARIA when developing any web interface.
